The {{nihongo|Amabe clan genealogy|海部氏系図|Amabe-shi Keizu||draft}} is a famous document housed at Kono Shrine. It is from early [[Heian period]], it is considered the oldest family tree in Japan. The clan claims descent from Amenohoakari, and served as at the ''[[kuni no miyatsuko]]'' of [[Tanba Province]] before it was divided into Tamba and Tango. The document records 82 generations of descent from Amenohoakari. It was designated a National Treasure in 1972.<ref name="Bunka1">{{cite web |title=海部氏系図 |trans-title=Amebe shikeizu |url=https://kunishitei.bunka.go.jp/heritage/detail/201/777 |accessdate=August 20, 2020 |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |language=Japanese}}</ref>

In ''{{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|en}}'', the descendants of {{ill|Amatsuhikone|en}}, {{ill|Ame-no-hohi|en}}, and {{ill|Amanomichine|en}}, together with the descendants of Amenohoakari are referred to as {{ill|Tenson-zoku|fr||ja|天孫族|zh|8=en|10=simple|11=User:Immanuelle/Tenson-zoku}} (天孫族). The ''{{ill|Tenson-zoku|fr||ja|天孫族|zh|8=en|10=simple|11=User:Immanuelle/Tenson-zoku}}'' descended from {{ill|Takamagahara|en}} (Plain of High {{ill|Heaven|en}}) to {{ill|Owari Province|Owari|en}} and {{ill|Tanba Province|lt=Tanba|en|}} provinces, and are considered to be the ancestors of {{ill|Owari clan|lt=Owari|en|}}, {{ill|Tsumori clan|lt=Tsumori|ja|津守氏|en}}, {{ill|Amabe clan|lt=Amabe|ja|海部氏|en}}, and {{ill|Tanba clan|lt=Tanba|ja|丹波氏|en}} clans.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/959773242|title=Shinsen Shōjiroku (新撰姓氏錄)|last=Hanawa|first=Hokiichi|date=1983|publisher=Onkogakkai|location=Japan|oclc=959773242|en}}</ref>

