{{Promising draft|reason=the high amount of work put into it over a long time, see edit history}}


{{Expand Japanese|天孫族}}
{{complex}}

{{ill|Tenson-zoku|fr||ja|天孫族|zh|天孫民族|8=en:draft|9=|10=simple|11=User:Immanuelle/Tenson-zoku|12=ko|13=천손족|14=uk|15=Тенсон Зоку|12=draft|12=draft}} (天孫族) is a generic term for ancient people that established the {{ill|Yamato kingship|en}}, which appears in the [[Kojiki]] and the [[Nihon Shoki]] and which is told in Japanese mythology. The ''{{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|en|4=fr|12=draft|12=draft}}'' defines "Tenson" as the offspring of {{ill|Amenohoakari|en|4=simple|5=User:Immanuelle/Amenohoakari|6=fr|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref name="yu-2023a" /> who it identifies with {{ill|Nigihayahi|ja|ニギハヤヒ|fr|6=en:draft|8=simple|9=User:Immanuelle/Nigihayahi}}.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Shoki Mononobe-uji no Keifu (1) Kokigi no Heya (初期物部氏の系譜 (1) 古樹紀之房間)|last=Hoga|first=Toshio|year=2007|location=Japan}}</ref> It mentions that the [[Imperial House of Japan|Imperial Family]], the {{ill|Mononobe clan|en|4=fr|5=clan Mononobe|12=draft|12=draft}} and an ancient tribe of {{ill|Hayato people|lt=Hayato|en||fr|Hayato|12=draft|12=draft}} descended from the Tenson tribe.<ref name="yu-2023a">{{Cite web|last=Yu|first=A. C.|title=Tenson-zoku (Tenson Tribe) - Japanese Wiki Corpus|url=https://www.japanesewiki.com/literature/Tenson-zoku%20(Tenson%20Tribe).html|access-date=2023-12-11|website=www.japanesewiki.com|publisher={{ill|National Institute of Information and Communications Technology|en}}}}</ref>

The Tenson tribe descended from [[Takamagahara|Takamagahara]] to conquer {{nihongo|'''{{ill|Ashihara no Nakatsukuni|en||fr|12=draft|12=draft}}'''|葦原の中つ国|''The middle country of {{ill|reed bed|en|lt=reed beds|reed bed|simple|user:immanuelle/reed bed|12=draft|12=draft}}''}} in the [[Kyūshū|Kyūshū]] region. Led by [[Emperor Jimmu|Emperor Jimmu]] they advanced east through [[Chūgoku region|Chugoku]] region to the [[Kansai region|Kansai region]]. Vanquishing the ruling families across western Japan they established the [[List of emperors of Japan|Yamato dynasty]] ({{ill|Wakoku|en}}) which was ruled by the {{ill|Okimi|lt=Great King of Yamato|en|4=simple|5=User:Immanuelle/Okimi|12=draft|12=draft}} ([[Emperor of Japan|emperor]]). The dynasty expanded its power to [[Chūbu region|Chubu]] and [[Kantō region|Kanto]] regions and developed into Japan as we know it today.<ref name="yu-2023a" />
== Genealogy ==
The {{nihongo|Amabe clan genealogy|海部氏系図|Amabe-shi Keizu||draft}} is a famous document housed at Kono Shrine. It is from early [[Heian period|Heian period]], it is considered the oldest family tree in Japan. The clan claims descent from {{ill|Amenohoakari|en|4=simple|5=User:Immanuelle/Amenohoakari|6=fr|12=draft|12=draft}}, and served as at the ''[[kuni no miyatsuko|kuni no miyatsuko]]'' of {{ill|Tamba Province|lt=Tanba Province|en||12=draft|12=draft}} before it was divided into Tamba and Tango. The document records 82 generations of descent from {{ill|Amenohoakari|en|4=simple|5=User:Immanuelle/Amenohoakari|6=fr|12=draft|12=draft}}. It was designated a National Treasure in 1972.<ref name="Bunka1">{{cite web|title=海部氏系図|trans-title=Amebe shikeizu|url=https://kunishitei.bunka.go.jp/heritage/detail/201/777|publisher={{ill|Agency for Cultural Affairs|en}}|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 20, 2020|12=draft|12=draft}}</ref>

In ''{{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|en|4=fr|12=draft|12=draft}}'', the descendants of {{ill|Amatsuhikone|en|4=fr|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ame-no-hohi|en|4=fr|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Amanomichine|ja|天道根命|en:draft|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Amanomichine|8=fr|12=draft|12=draft}}, together with the descendants of Amenohoakari are referred to as {{ill|Tenson-zoku|fr||ja|天孫族|zh|天孫民族|en:draft||simple|User:Immanuelle/Tenson-zoku|ko|천손족|uk|Тенсон Зоку|12=draft|12=draft}} (天孫族). The ''{{ill|Tenson-zoku|fr||ja|天孫族|zh|天孫民族|en:draft||simple|User:Immanuelle/Tenson-zoku|ko|천손족|uk|Тенсон Зоку|12=draft|12=draft}}'' descended from [[Takamagahara]] (Plain of High {{ill|Heaven|en}}) to {{ill|Owari Province|lt=Owari|en|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Tamba Province|lt=Tanba|en||12=draft|12=draft}} provinces, and are considered to be the ancestors of {{ill|Owari clan|lt=Owari|en||fr|clan Owari|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tsumori clan|lt=Tsumori|ja|津守氏|en|6=fr|7=Clan Tsumori|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Amabe clan|lt=Amabe|ja|海部氏|en|6=fr|7=Clan Amabe|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Tanba clan|lt=Tanba|ja|丹波氏|1=Tanba clan|2=ja|3=丹波氏|4=ko|5=단바씨|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Tanba clan|en|6=fr|7=Clan Tanba|12=draft|12=draft}} clans.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/959773242|title=Shinsen Shōjiroku (新撰姓氏錄)|last=Hanawa|first=Hokiichi|date=1983|publisher=Onkogakkai|location=Japan|oclc=959773242|en}}</ref>


However, it is clear that ''{{nihongo|'''Amabe clan genealogy'''|海部氏系図|Amabe-shi Keizu}},'' which records these four clans as descendants of {{ill|Amenohoakari|en|4=simple|5=User:Immanuelle/Amenohoakari|6=fr|12=draft|12=draft}}, is a forged document, and that these clans actually descended from the {{ill|List of water deities|lt=sea deity|en|12=draft|12=draft}} [[Watatsumi|Watatsumi]]. In addition, Owari clan's genealogy includes the great-grandson of Watatsumi, {{ill|Takakuraji|ja|高倉下|en|6=fr|12=draft|12=draft}}, as their ancestor, and this is considered to be the original genealogy.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Tango no Amabe-shi no Shutsuji to sono ichizoku, Kokigi no Heya (丹後の海部氏の出自とその一族)|last=Hoga|first=Toshio|year=2006|location=Japan}}</ref>


